content.problemStatement:
A constructor in Java is a special method that is used to initialize objects. It is **automatically called** when an **object** of a class is **created**. Constructors help in setting up initial values or executing startup code when the object is formed.

- The constructor must have the **same name as the class**.
- A constructor **does not have a return type** (not even `void`).

---

**Syntax:**
```java
class ClassName {
    // Default Constructor
    ClassName() {
        // Initialization code
    }
}
```

---

**Example: Default Constructor**

```java
class Seedit {
    // Constructor - This is the default constructor
    // It is called automatically when an object of the class is created
    SEED-IT() {
        System.out.println("Default Constructor is called!");
    }



    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating an object, which triggers the default constructor
        SEED-IT obj1 = new SEED-IT();

    }
}
```
**Explanation:**
- **Default Constructor**: If you do not explicitly write a default constructor, Java automatically provides a default constructor for the class (with no parameters and no implementation). The default constructor is used when you create an object without passing any arguments.

